=== Amendment: gate cycle 2 Major finding fix (case-sensitive Select-String
for the Spec-Review-Status header field) ===

Finding: `plugins/sdd-review-loop/scripts/spec-review-precheck.ps1:187`'s
`Select-String -Pattern '^Spec-Review-Status:\s*(.*)$'` used PowerShell's
default CASE-INSENSITIVE matching (a cmdlet-level default, not an operator
this task's cycle-1 sweep covered), so it also matched a header field
written as `SPEC-REVIEW-STATUS:` or `spec-review-status:` -- values the
`.sh` original's `sed -n 's/^Spec-Review-Status:[[:space:]]*//p'` (sed BRE,
always case-sensitive) never matches, leaving `$status` empty and
`requirements.md must declare Spec-Review-Status: Pending` firing for the
WRONG reason on a genuinely-cased header, or -- worse -- silently accepting
a differently-cased header as if it correctly declared the field. Cycle 1's
sweep instruction and this task's own follow-on sweep were scoped to
PowerShell comparison OPERATORS (`-match`/`-eq`/`-contains`/etc.); this is
the first cmdlet/language-feature-level gap found, confirming the vulnerability
class is broader than the operator set alone.

Fix: added `-CaseSensitive` to the `Select-String` call at line 187
(single-parameter fix, no other change to that line).

=== Cmdlet/feature-level sweep (NOT operator-level -- the class explicitly
requested this cycle): every case-insensitive-by-default PowerShell
mechanism in the file ===

| Mechanism | Occurrence(s) | .sh original semantics | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|
| `Select-String` (all uses) | Line 187 only (single call site in the whole file) | `sed -n 's/^Spec-Review-Status:[[:space:]]*//p'` -- sed BRE, always case-sensitive (no `sed` case-insensitive flag used) | **DIVERGENCE (the reported Major).** Fixed: added `-CaseSensitive`. |
| `Get-ChildItem -Filter`/`-Include`/`-Exclude` | Line 447: `Get-ChildItem -LiteralPath $previousAttempt -Directory -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue` | `.sh` original: `find "$previous_attempt" -maxdepth 1 -type d -name 'round-*'` | Safe -- no `-Filter`/`-Include`/`-Exclude` parameter is used at all; `Get-ChildItem -Directory` here enumerates every subdirectory unconditionally (verified empirically: a probe directory containing both `round-1` and `ROUND-2` returns BOTH names from `Get-ChildItem -Directory` with no filtering). The actual case enforcement happens entirely downstream, in the already-fixed (gate cycle 1) `-cmatch '^round-[1-3]$'` `Where-Object` clause immediately after. No cmdlet-level gap here; already covered. |
| `-like`/`-notlike` | none | -- | N/A -- operator not used anywhere in this file. |
| `-split`/`-isplit`/`-csplit` | none | -- | N/A -- operator not used anywhere in this file (the evaluator's warning that regex `-split` defaults to case-insensitive is correct in general, but moot here since this file never splits a string via a regex-based pattern -- all field extraction goes through `Select-String`/`ConvertFrom-Json`/`.Groups[...]`). |
| `[regex]::Match`/`[regex]::IsMatch`/`[Text.RegularExpressions.Regex]::Replace` | Line 505-509: `[Text.RegularExpressions.Regex]::Replace($content, '(?m)^Spec-Review-Status:[ \t]*Passed[ \t]*(\r?)$', 'Spec-Review-Status: Pending$1')` (the `--reset`-time status-field rewrite) | `.sh` original: `sed 's/^Spec-Review-Status:[[:space:]]*Passed[[:space:]]*$/Spec-Review-Status: Pending/'` -- sed BRE, case-sensitive | Verified SAFE empirically, not just by documentation: the static `[regex]::Replace(string, pattern, replacement)` overload used here takes no `RegexOptions` argument, and .NET's `Regex` class is case-sensitive by default (`RegexOptions.None`), UNLIKE PowerShell's `-replace` operator (which defaults to case-insensitive). Confirmed with a live probe: `[Text.RegularExpressions.Regex]::Replace("SPEC-REVIEW-STATUS: Passed`n", '(?m)^Spec-Review-Status:[ \t]*Passed[ \t]*(\r?)$', 'Spec-Review-Status: Pending$1')` left the uppercase-header input UNCHANGED (`changed: False`) -- exactly matching `sed`'s case-sensitive behavior. No fix needed. |
| String instance methods (`.StartsWith`/`.EndsWith`/`.Equals`/`.IndexOf`/`.Contains`/`.Replace`) | none used directly (grep for `\.StartsWith\|\.EndsWith\|\.Equals(\|\.IndexOf\|\.Contains(\|\.Replace(` returns zero matches) | -- | N/A -- the file never calls a raw .NET string instance method for comparison; every string-identity check goes through the file's own `Test-OrdinalEqual` helper (`[string]::Equals($Left, $Right, [StringComparison]::Ordinal)`, explicitly ordinal/case-sensitive by construction), and the two SHA-256 helpers use `.ToLower()` only for canonicalizing HEX OUTPUT (not for a comparison), which introduces no case-sensitivity gap since both sides of every hash comparison are independently lower-cased the same way before an ordinal compare. |
| `Sort-Object` (case-insensitive, culture-aware, by default) | 9 call sites: lines 96, 97 (`Test-KeysExact` property-name sets), 223, 343, 347, 355, 356 (manifest-entry arrays sorted by `path`), 274 (reviewer `role` values), 448 (`--reset` round-number integers) | `.sh` original: `jq`'s `sort_by(...)`/`sort` -- byte-wise/codepoint order, always case-sensitive | Reviewed individually, no functional divergence found (documented per-site below); no fix applied. |
| `switch (...)` (plain, no `-wildcard`/`-regex`; case-insensitive by default) | Line 227: `switch ($Role) { 'spec-reviewer-a' {...} 'spec-reviewer-b' {...} default {...} }` inside `Test-ValidateReviewerOutput` | `.sh` original: `case "$role" in spec-reviewer-a) ...;; spec-reviewer-b) ...;; *) return 1;; esac` -- bash `case` glob matching, case-sensitive (no `shopt -s nocasematch`) | Confirmed case-insensitive empirically (`switch ($Role)` with `$Role = 'SPEC-REVIEWER-A'` matched the `'spec-reviewer-a'` branch). NOT exploitable: `$Role` is ALWAYS an internal literal (`'spec-reviewer-a'`/`'spec-reviewer-b'`) supplied by this script's own two call sites (`Test-ValidateContract` lines 367-368), never a value parsed from JSON evidence. The JSON-sourced field that this function actually validates against untrusted input, `$data.role`, is separately checked via `Test-OrdinalEqual $data.role $Role` (line 216, ordinal/case-sensitive) before the `switch` is ever reached. No fix applied (not a real gap); documented for completeness per the amendment's explicit request to report every mechanism checked, not only the ones fixed. |
| `-in`/`-notin`/`-ilike`/`-inotmatch`/`-ireplace` (explicit case-insensitive variants) | none | -- | N/A -- not used. |

=== Sort-Object per-site review (why no functional divergence exists) ===

`Sort-Object`'s default comparer is case-insensitive and culture-aware,
unlike `jq`'s `sort`/`sort_by` (byte-wise, case-sensitive). This IS a
different comparer than the `.sh` original uses, but a different comparer
only produces an OBSERVABLE divergence if it changes the pass/fail OUTCOME
of a subsequent check. Reviewed each site:

- Lines 96-97 (`Test-KeysExact`): sorts two sets of JSON PROPERTY NAMES,
  then compares them index-by-index via `Test-OrdinalEqual` (ordinal). This
  is a SET-equality check implemented as "sort both consistently, then
  compare pairwise" -- since both arrays are sorted by the SAME comparer
  (whichever one `Sort-Object` uses), any two equal sets of strings always
  land in identical index order, and any two UNEQUAL sets always produce a
  mismatch somewhere in the pairwise ordinal comparison, regardless of which
  total-order comparer was used for sorting. This schema's key names are
  also all mutually distinct even case-insensitively (e.g. no key differs
  from another ONLY by case), so there is no comparer-dependent grouping
  ambiguity either. Safe by construction.
- Lines 223, 343, 347, 355-356 (manifest-entry arrays sorted by `.path`,
  compared via `Test-ManifestArraysEqual`'s ordinal per-element check): same
  "sort both sides with the same comparer, then compare pairwise ordinally"
  shape as above -- the comparer choice affects sort ORDER, not the ordinal
  EQUALITY verdict at each resulting position, and the canonical path set
  compared here is fixed and mutually case-distinct (`requirements.md`,
  `acceptance-tests.md`, the precheck file, the calibration file, optionally
  `investigation.md`, optionally the round's `integrated-summary.json`) so
  no two entries could ever collide or reorder ambiguously due to a
  case-insensitive vs. case-sensitive comparer. Safe.
- Line 274 (`$roles = @($reviewers | ForEach-Object { $_.role } | Sort-Object)`,
  then compared against the LITERAL strings `'spec-reviewer-a'`/
  `'spec-reviewer-b'` via `Test-OrdinalEqual`): the two canonical role
  strings differ only in their final character (`a` vs `b`, both already
  lowercase), so case-insensitive and case-sensitive sort orders coincide
  for legitimate data. For adversarial/malformed data (e.g. a role value
  actually written as `SPEC-REVIEWER-A`), sort placement may differ from
  what `jq sort` would produce, but the FINAL enforcement is
  `Test-OrdinalEqual $roles[0] 'spec-reviewer-a'` (ordinal) -- a
  differently-cased role value fails this check regardless of which sort
  order placed it at index 0 or 1, so the case-sensitivity of the actual
  security-relevant comparison is unaffected by the sort comparer. Safe.
- Line 448 (`Sort-Object` on `[int]`-converted round numbers): sorts
  integers, not strings; case has no meaning for numeric comparison. Safe,
  not applicable.

Conclusion: `Sort-Object`'s case-insensitive default is a REAL semantic
difference from `jq sort`/`sort_by`, but in every one of this file's 9 call
sites the actual accept/reject decision is enforced by a SEPARATE ordinal
comparison (`Test-OrdinalEqual`) applied after sorting, not by the sort
order itself -- so no site was found where the comparer choice can change
the script's accept/reject verdict. No fix applied to any `Sort-Object`
call site.

